'''Sahohiko no Mikoto''' (狭穂彦王, dates of birth and death unknown, died in the 10th month of the 5th year of Emperor Suinin's reign) was a member of the imperial family (royalty) in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, he is referred to as '''Sahohiko no Mikoto''', while in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}, he is called '''Sahobiko no Mikoto''' (沙本毘古王).
== Overview ==
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, in the 5th year of Emperor Suinin's reign, Sahohiko ordered his sister, {{ill|Saho-hime|lt=Sahohime no Mikoto|ja|狭穂姫命|12=draft|12=draft}}, to assassinate the emperor. When the plan failed, he initiated a rebellion but was ultimately cornered. Both Sahohiko and his sister committed suicide within the fortifications of an earthen fortress made of rice sheaves. This rebellion, known as the {{ill|Rebellion of Sahohime and Sahohiko|ja|狭穂姫命#狭穂彦王の叛乱|12=draft|12=draft}}, is considered one of the most vividly described events in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Genealogy ==
The genealogy of Sahohiko is most detailed in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}. According to it, he was the son of {{ill|Hikozahowake no Mikoto|ja|彦坐王|12=draft|12=draft}}, making him a grandson of {{ill|Emperor Kaika|ja|開化天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. His mother was Sahono Ōkurumitoori (沙本之大闇見戸売), the daughter of Kasuga Takakuni Katsutorihime (春日建国勝戸売). He had several siblings, including {{ill|Oyamoto no Mikoto|ja|袁邪本王|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ancestor of Kudonowake and Kotoomi Kano, {{ill|Murobiko no Mikoto|ja|室毘古王|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ancestor of Wakasa Mimibetsu, and {{ill|Saho-hime|lt=Sahohime no Mikoto|ja|狭穂姫命|12=draft|12=draft}}, who became the empress of Emperor Suinin. == See Also == * {{ill|List of people before the Asuka period|ja|飛鳥時代以前の人物一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}
